"'''¡30-30!'''" ({{lang-es|¡Treinta-treinta!}}) was a [[Mexico|Mexican]] artists' group of [[Mexican revolution|revolutionary]] anti-academic painters, that took its name from the [[.30-30 Winchester]] rifle. The group existed from 1928 to 1930, and had around about 30 members. They published five manifestos and a journal in three issues.<ref>David Craven: [https://books.google.com/books?id=Z91vz-yr5ecC&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=Ram%C3%B3n+Alva+de+la+Canal+%2230-30%22&source=bl&ots=ZCdTeqtQYw&sig=_yvmsq_z3MJaZ_hFnq8eq4ACpeY&hl=en&ei=-7gzSuyfLZKQsAbr66DFCQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3 ''Art and Revolution in Latin America, 1910-1990''], 2006, p. 63.</ref>
